task.summary: - I'm in the progress of either entirely fucking the project, or making a good break through to make the project more organized and testable. I'm not really sure which way it's going yet though. XD - [skip-ci] - Just commited this before so it's not too annoying to roll back if everything turns to shit. - Professional 10/10
- Too many changes... Not gonna even bother listing it. [skip-ci] - Regardless we're closer to having a more generic, decoupled, and more testable version of Commandler.

- Lots of changes again, not gonna bother writing every change. [skip-ci] - I know, I'm awesome. :ablobaww: - Regardless, it now compiles and we have a testable (but broken) build. - Tomorrow I'll continue cleaning up, patching bugs and making Commandler (less generics everywhere hopefully) as easy to implement for platforms as possible.

- Changed how we register parsers to make it more friendly to generic types and primitive types - Fixed "bug" with generics, in runtime we have 2 methods, the generic method that returns Object, and the implemented method which returns String (look into this) - 46% code coverage and 3 out of 3 basic tests passing. ^-^ - [skip-ci]

- [skip-ci] - Adding more documentation to classes - Setting default values with public static final fields in annotations - Give some components more appropriate names and pulled out common code which users probably won't want to override if replacing the component method - Removed storing developers from confiler (discord specific) - Changed how modules are hidden to now use a 0 length string rather than a seperate boolean - Prepped @Module to have submodules (Commandler doesn't actually have this yet though) - Cleaned up the Number parser params with a public static final variable - Fixed a big in normalising command input
- String commandler now doesn't nest commandler package in commandler package. :thinking: - String commandler now has NumberBuilder for returning numbers - Creating modules in StringCommandler rather than in test cases (cleaner and makes tests clearer and modules reusable between tests) - Fixed bug with arrays and made test module to run through some array related commands - Made generic enum parser which can parse any enum if a specific parser wasn't made for it using default logic - WIP making a default help command for StringCommandler

- Added log4j2 binding for slf4j so we now see logs when testing / developing - Now updated to Java 10 and moved to OpenJDK - Created new test case for Overload (which was broken, and still broken) - Added some logging around StringCommandler, should add more to Commandler/StringCommandler later - Everywhere we used Module, we must now explicitly import Module to avoid using the default java.lang.Module introduced in Java 9/10. :thinking: May think about a rename due to this. - Removed logging when registering commands (as this just spams up the box pointlessly) - [skip-ci] (Tomorrow I'll try get around to updating the CI to be compatible with this multi-project build) - Bed time for Sethi ^-^

- Started implementing IMisuseHandler and creating default handling methods for each type of error Commandler may report. - Started making negative test cases which should report default handling methods. - _Lots_ of code clean up in preparation for implementing Overloads again. (this time without constantly breaking it!) - OMG MORE DOCS! \\(^-^)/ Am best doccer :ablobaww: - Removed all custom exceptions and using Java exceptions instead - Added more options to boolean parser for true/false - Deleted AbstractMetaCommand and MetaOverload, Overloads will now also just be MetaCommands right up. - Made all logging/exception messages private static final variables - Created the @Partial annotation (not implemented yet), this should be attached to array parameters if it's not big deal if some of the list parsed fine, but not all - Updated dependencies - Unknown error now occurs on any uncaught exception. - [skip-ci]
We're doing really well. ^-^ I didn't work much today 'cause meh but still achieved a fair bit, project is getting cleaner and better as we go.

- Now have a minimal (incomplete but functional) implementation of Overloads - Have a negative test case for with overloads and fixed bug - Fixed bug in string dispatcher to prevent logging error twice - Cleaned up line breaks (thank you Arthur. <3) - Added validation to prevent same method from having both @Command and @Overload - [skip-ci]
- Just went through all code and removed the extra line breaks from the docs, as well as removed all unused imports from classes - [skip-ci] 59% code coverage \\(^-^)/

- Made more test cases - created default parser for characters - changed command input return to command event which can not be overriden as well - ^The above also allows reusing the same dispatcher code in implementations, overridable if they want to process commands differently - Removed some redundant code - cleaned up packagaes - 64% coverage - [skip-ci]

- Aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa - Trying to currently reduce the total number of generics used/seen in Commandler and the implementations of it - Implemented a default help command and corrected the test for it to reflect this, we will only be making a default help command, not a default help module, implementations will have to cover that themself (unless I change my mind otherwise) - Pulling default implementations into the interface rather than abstract class where possible - Cleaned up some areas, gave classes/variables more apropriate names and added a getMessage method to the command event. - Moved the delete message method to JDA specifically rather than the generic as it'll probably not many platforms we can delete others message - Changed JDACommmandler a lot to reflect the changes made, it's almost entirely set up except it needs it's to override the builder build method to accomodate the fact we want to make it so we have a method for getting as embed and another for getting as string. - Moving Search from a special annotation to just plain validation (if the item returned when parsing doesn't suit the scope) - Put the search scope enum inside the Search annotation since I just didn't feel like having a data package just for one enum _shrugs_ 66% code coverage guys! ^-^ Hopefully tomorrow if I want to die enough CommandlerBot will be back online, and in fact thanks to how decoupled it is, I could even copy and paste commands from String Commandler and they'll work with no change required. :o - [skip-ci]
